More usual is castling, as my opponent in the previous game did. This does ensure the e-pawn is defended and releases the dark-squared Bishop though.
Once again the pin is prevented.
Last time I played 9...Bb7 and my Bishop ended up being something of a liability. This time I decide on the more usual continuation.
Something of a fight for d4 going on here. This also means White can play Nbd2 without blocking this Bishop.
A fairly standard set-up for Black, I would have thought - I just need a place for my light-squared Bishop if it's not going to b7.
In the previous game the White Rook was already on e1, leaving f1 for the Knight on its journey to the K-side. Perhaps one of the advantages of 5.0-0 as opposed to 5.d3?
At any rate, my Rook gets to the file first. As in my last game, I'm planning to return my Bishop to f8.
I'm not sure what this achieves other than preventing b4 - maybe White is planning that move himself? It's certainly not on my list.
Perhaps over-cautious this time, since I haven't played h6 so there is no target for a piece sac.

This is a bit of a puzzle, and rather counter to usual Lopez plans. After all, the Bishop has just moved from here. Perhaps the idea is to re-route the Bishop to a2, hence the a-pawn advance? Since White has made five moves with this Bishop it seems to lose tempi somewhere along the way.
Happy to offer my invariably useless Bishop up for a swap.
So White has moved the Bishop five times only to allow it to be exchanged... I don't want to allow 16.d5 forking my pieces anyway.
This was another surprise, as I expected a recapture with the Knight, though that would allow me to open the game up with 16...Nxe4 17.dxc5 perhaps.
Now I get to have the same pawn chain I had in the previous game, and with a tempo, as the Queen must retreat.
Adding to the support of my e-pawn - I want to re-route my Knight to the K-side, since that's where the action, if any, is going to be, and I can't go to e7 without defending the e-pawn first.
White closes up the centre...
And drives my Knight to where it was headed anyway.
The start of a K-side attack? There's not a lot of support. Or is the Knight heading for f5 to attack my backward d-pawn - a pawn that was vulnerable in the previous game?
At any rate, I don't want to allow the Bishop to g5. Once again the Bishop on f8 comes in handy.
White's forces are massing. Since the a1 Rook has been used for this move I',m assuming White wants the other Rook on f1 to support a pawn advance.
Adding to control of g5, a square that was important in my previous game.
This attack is taking a long time to set up, one of the reasons I tend to avoid playing the Ruy Lopez as White. I'm a more patient defender than I am an attacker.
Now the Knight won't be going to f5, as it might be tricky to defend a pawn there after an exchange. I have time, I think, to rearrange my pieces, with a Knight on g6 and my Queen on f6.
The Knight, foiled, returns to f3.
I'm starting to wonder where all this manouvering is headed.
Now I can play Nf4, though White will probably be glad to get rid of his Bishop, which doesn't have too many squares.
The pawn advance must be coming?
I feel I have weathered a storm that never really broke, and have quite a reasonable position.
White must think so too, since he offers an exchange.
But I'll keep my Queen on the board for now, thank you!
A good time to advance, since I don't want to open the game up with my Queen here, and I don't want to allow fxe5 with my Queen here either.
Maybe I should have exchanged Queens?
Opening up an attack on f7, a crucial spot in the previous game.
Suddenly it's looking ugly, since White has created a passed pawn, albeit one that can't go far right now.
Avoiding potential checks along the g1-a7 diagonal. And perhaps preparing a pawn-storm?
My position is suddenly looking vulnerable, though my King seems well defended.
With White's dark-squared Bishop gone and the Knights far away the prospect of an h6 sac recedes, and I want to block that pawn right away.
This Knight hasn't anywhere else to go and isn't doing much on h2.
Still, happy to remove a potential attacker.
Not a pretty move, I admit, but it adds cover to f7 and I'm planning to get my Queen to d7.
Surprisingly, White accepts the exchange, which now I'm happier with.
Not a lot I can do to guard f5 though.
Clearly White wants to hold on to the Knight. 36.Nf5 would have been more of a nuisance though.
Another game where I'd be happy with a draw!
Here comes that pawn storm...
The Queens are gone, so I feel I can meet pawn with pawn. Nasty hole on f5 though.
Looks like White wants to attack down the h-file.
I match his King advance and protect my h-pawn.
The White Knight has a fairly tortuous route if it wants to go to f5; maybe it's clearing the file for the ROoks instead?
f7 is covered well now.
I see - it's the Rook that wants the square. Still, I'd have thought a Knight more dangerous here?
Rather rendering my Bishop bad, but then it's job right now is preventing the passed pawn's advance.
Heading to h5, possibly.
I'm lining up defences and think my position will hold.
Just where this Knight is going I have little idea.
Just in case White has ideas of advancing the h-pawn to break up my defence.
Ah - he's finally decided to put the Knight on f5!
I will get the Bishop out from attack before it happens.
Success!
The passed pawn is now looking a bit ominous.
I don't want the h-file opening - I have enough problems in the middle!
Better, anyway, to have the Rooks doubled here.
Tempting the pawn to advance...
It does. Now...
I can attack it with more than White can defend with, since his Rook can't go to d3. Had I used the other Rook I might have been successful.

Wicked move! I have three options. White is probably hoping for 48...Kg7 49.Rxf6, when 49...Bxd6 wins back the pawn only to fall foul of 50.Nf5+ winning the Bishop. 48...Kf7 49.Rxf6+ might not lead to a mate, but the position is horrible. So there's only one option left...
I quite miss the killer 49.Rxf6+!
So does White.
Now I am a pawn down but crucially can control the only open file, since White can't get a Rook to d3.
He's rather left shuffling Rooks, while I probably have a spare square. He won't want me checking on d7.

I thought his best chance might be down the h-file with 52.Rh1,with the intention of opening the file for a Rook. To have any chance of a draw I need to keep the position close. It struck me, though, that getting my Bishop to f4 would also create counterplay with possible checks on g3, maybe winning the h-pawn, however risky.
Clearly exchanging loses fairly quickly.
My draw offer was turned down around now.
Not sure how helpful this is to White.

It allows me a tempo with the Bishop. I wondered if White might risk 55.Rxe3 Rxe3 56.Rd1, when I either concede the open file and win the b-pawn or allow an exchange with 56...Rd3 57.Rxd3 cxd3. The White King will win the passed pawn, then it may be possible for the White King to penetrate.
But he doesn't!
So I go to the square I am aiming at.
Clinging to my open file; allowing an exchange is no good despite the resulting passed pawn - it will soon be snuffled up.
Perhaps White hopes to bring the King across to guard a square on which to place a Rook? But with my Bishop on f4 that's going to be difficult; I have d2 and d3 covered.

57...Rd2+ was tempting, I must admit, had I thought I could win those Q-side pawns with the Bishop. As it is I just keep my Rook on the open file. The better move, which I quite missed, was 57...Re1, for White's e-pawn can't be defended.
Maybe 59.Ke2 Rd6 60.Rc1 with a hope of 61.Rd1 to challenge the open file might have worked had I not had 60...Rd2+ to drive the King back again.
As long as I control the open file I can't see how the White Rooks can challenge, especially now I have d2 covered by the Bishop as well.
And indeed White offered the draw, which I accepted.

This is the "Advance Variation".  For years computer analysis has suggested that this move only gives White equality.  If White wants to play for an advantage he should try the Tarrasch variation with 3. Nd2.  The reason this works is because it is easier for White to defend his center while enjoying a slight space advantage and better bishops.
Here I often see people falter with 4. Nf3?! and then after 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nge7! and 6... Nbc6 Black is doing better because he has the stronger center.
If White doesn't play this, his game is terrible after 4... cxd4.
All the emphasis will be on attacking the center.
6. dxc5?! Bxc5 temporarily gives Black the initiative because White has to defend f2.

I have seen this move quite a bit lately.

Other good choices include : 6. a3, 6. Bd3!? and 6. Qb3!?

I have known for years that computer analysis prefers this move, but I didn't necessarily know why.  The key is that it is important to attack the center before White castles, after which he has some tricks like after 6... Nh6 7. O-O threatening 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. b4, or say after 6... Nh6 7. O-O cxd4 White can try 8. b4! dxc3 9. b5 and 10. Nxc3 without worrying about the safety of his king.

Preparing to go to f5.   Obviously not 8. Bxh6 Qxb2 although a few people have played this against me.  Black can also play 7... Ne7.

The key for White to maintain equality is to now move the knight to c3 and a4.  The moves 8. Nc3 Nf5 9. Na4 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Qb6 11. Na4 leads to a draw.  If 10. Kf1 b5 11. Nc3 b4 12. Nb5 and then 12... h5 is miniscule better for Black.
Not necessarily the strongest.
It is common in this opening for White to hold the pawn this way.

This doesn't particularly give Black an advantage.  Computer analysis barely prefers 9... h5.

Now not 10. Bc3 Nfxd4.  Playing either knight to d2 drops the d4 pawn.
Although this might look bad for White, the game is equal.

This bishop retreat is questionable.  It might be better to wait.

Computer analysis likes both 10... O-O and 10... f6.
Attempting to undermine the center.  Now if 12. Kg2?! fxe5 13. dxe5 Bc5 with a slight edge for Black.
Here White absolutely has to play 13. Nc3 O-O (capturing d4 is losing after14. Na4) 14. Na4 Qc7 15. Kg2.
This move is a disaster.  Not only does he take a defender off of d4, but it is now too late to try to save himself with Nc3.

There could be some tricky lines if Black doesn't castle, and it is more important to build up strength on the F file than it is to capture the pawn right away.

Now 14. Nc3 loses a piece to 14... Bxe5 because of the threat of Ne3+.
15. Kg2 is about the same.
The pawn finally falls.  Black wants to trade pieces to go into a favorable endgame.

At first this seems counterintuitive because taking with the Queen would result in the trade of pieces.  However, Black has a trick up his sleeve.

White needs to play 17. Bd1 and then Black's best response would be 17... e5
But instead he falls for a two move tactic.
With the discovered threat of mate on f2.

White can't even take back because of the mate threat.

The game is essentially over.

Erika starts off with her usual.  Of course, I told her that this is the most common opening.  And, not surprisingly, her opponents generally respond with 1...e5 which is also how my opponents often respond.

This is now the Philidor's Defense.  It's sound but not the best defense.  Slightly better would've been to respond with the Petrov's Defense which is 2...Nf6, or 2...Nc6, which is how my opponents respond.  And, the reason being is because of what Erika should do next.

I can understand this move since it develops.  But, best would've been 3.d4.  As noted, Erika, after 2.Nf3, when your opponent advances a pawn just one square, 3.d4 is the best way to follow up since you're breaking through in the center.  As now, you have line open for both of your Bishops, and even they're not out, yet, your Bc1 and Bf1 are both more mobile and, thus, active.

I don't like this move that much since his Dark Squared Bishop is not as mobile as it could be.  As of the moment, it only covers 4 squares since the other path is gone.  This is why the Philidor's Defense isn't the best way to go.  If the d pawn hadn't blocked the Bishop, it would cover twice, so 8 squares.  It only seems minor, but how many squares a Bishop covers is also important as Grandmaster Susan Polgar has emphasized this.  As the amount they cover determines how mobile the Bishop is.  So, the more squares the merrier as they're more mobile.

?! Not the best was to go about.  Like before, I understand why Erika played this since it develops.  But, as I and others have discussed with her, this blocks the center pawn which is not the best way to go about.  Better was 4.Bc4 or 4.Bb5.  In this position, being that it wasn't the Spanish Opening, I would've played 4.Bc4, as his Nb8 has not yet been developed.  So, after 4...c6 or 4...a6 white loses a tempo since the Light Squared Bishop would be forced to retreat.

I think that black's intention is to get the Rook on an open file.  But, this is not the best way to go.  That works when you become a master or above, since I have seen this being done with deeper_insight.  But, where black is, better would be to continue developing.  As black is way behind.  Right now, Erika only has one piece that isn't developed, but black only has one piece developed.  So, despite material being level, I favor white's position and reckon that she has a slight advantage.
Bringing the monarch to safety which is a good way to go about.
We're finally seeing black develop another piece.  But, he still has two pieces left to bring into play.
Fianchettoing, as the idea is to complete her development.
Black is thinking along a similar line, but he's bringing a pawn chain with it.
As is Erika.  But, after fianchettoing, I would've completed it, as well as, my development with 7.Bb2.
Like Erika, black gets his King to safety, for now.
At once, Erika completes her development.  The only criticism on white is that he still has two pieces to bring out.

And, the reason behind that comment with black is because of this move which does not develop.  I believe that his idea was to get to his monarch to safer spot since Coach Stockel said that after castling, you should bring your King to the corner.  But, it's about knowing when to do that, and this was not the time.  Better was to continue developing with 8...Bb7 or 8...Nc6.  And, with that being said, I like white's position even better then before because of her next move as she's about to put some pressure against black.

Ignoring the pressure, black plays this.  I don't know why he moved here, but given that an exchange can't be avoided, I would've developed with 9...Nc6  This way, after exchanging with 10.bxa5, after recapturing, black would be able to complete his develop since there are squares for his Bc8.
As now, Erika has a threat against black which can be driven off.  There's only one move that would do it, but Erika would still wind up with a better position.  Ok, what should black do, Erika?

?? And, black overlooks it.  I don't know why he played this either, but the solution was 11...Be6.  That was the only way to save black, but Erika would still be much better off as black would be forced to exchange his Light Squared Bishop for her Ng5, after 12.Nxe6  As there was a similar position to this that I studied with Coach Stockel.  It involved mating with the Knight, and the only way to drive it off would've been with the Bishop which is exactly what happened.  He then said that the best continuation was to exchange the Knight for Bishop.  I agree with this because Grandmaster Susan Polgar implied that, in general, Bishops are favorable over Knights.  That's when she gave advise not to exchange without a good reason, Susan was, specifically, talking about Bishop for Knight.  But, with this move, Erika can mate in one, and unlike with her previous annotations, white will not miss it, this time around.  Well done!

There are two important lessons to be learned from this game.  First, bring your pieces ASAP.  For example, black only had one piece developed until his fifth and remained with 2 pieces undeveloped throughout the rest of the game.  That allowed Erika to develop an attack where she had an advantage as black would've been forced into an unfavorable exchange in order to avoid mate.  The second is something that cplusplus11 stressed, "You must be aware of all threats made by your opponents, checkmate and captures."  This was one of them, or as Grandmaster Susan Polgar puts it, "You must ask yourself, what does my opponent want."
White to play.
Although 3. d5 is technically better, it leads to the Benoni which is complicated, so White chooses to transpose to the English Opening.
What is the best move?

White chooses the Maroczy Bind.  This transposes to the Accelerated Dragon, where this formation is sometimes seen.

The advantage to White is that if Black doesn't know how to handle it properly, White will maintain a big edge.
Now White is only slightly better after 9... Nd7 10. Qd2 Qa5 11. O-O Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 13. Qxd4 Qb6 14. Qxb6 Nxb6.
Instead Black is having difficulty here.

A blunder.

Better is 11... Re8 12. b3 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Rc8.
With a discovered attack on the queen.
This should be winning for White, but he manages to screw it later.
Hoping to harass the Black Queen.
White has a critical decision to make here.

And fails.

White missed the tactics that follow after 16. Rac1.  Then if 16... Nxc4? 17. Bxc4 Qxc4 18. Nd5 with potential knight forks.  If 18... Qb5 19. Nc7 with a fork or 18... Qb3 19. Rc3 Qa4 20. Nb6 with a fork.
Although the material has equalized, White still has a strong advantage.

Which accomplishes nothing.

After 21. Rc7 Ke8 22. Qc1 Qa4 23. h4 Qb5 24. Bf2 Kd8 25. Rc2 Rc8 26. Rxc8+ Bxc8 27. Qh6 White has a technically winning game.

A mistake.

Black is equal after  22... Rc8 23. Rxc8+ Bxc8.   White should not fall for 23. Rxd7?? Qb1+ 24. Kf2 Rc2.

This runs into problems.

White needs to play 23. h4 to give his king room to escape. Then if 23... Ke8 24. Kh2 Rc8 25. Rxc8+ Bxc8 26. Qc1 Bd7 27. Qh6 Bc8 (27... Kd8 28. Qf8+) 28. Qxh7 Qc2 (28... Kd7 29. Bxf6) (28... Kf8 29. Qh8+) 29. Qg8+ Kd7 30. Bb6 with a winning position.

A blunder.

The game is roughly equal after 23... Qb1+ 24. Kf2 Rc8 25. Qh6+ Ke8 26. Kg3.
This has to be winning.  For example 24... Rc8 25. Rxd7 and after either 25... Qa1+ or 25... Rc1+ then 26. Kf2 is fine.
Black needs to allow 25... Rc8 26. Rxd7.
This will prove to be much worse.

This looks natural, but it is fatal.  

What is the best move for White?
This movie is a simple penetration into c7, but Stockfish 8 had a hard time seeing it.
White returns all of Black's blunders with a huge blunder of his own, missing the win with 28. Kg3 Ke8 29. Qc7 Kf7 30. Qxd7 Qe5+ 31. f4 Qc3+ 32. Kh4 Qe1+ 33. Kh3!
Needless to say, I overlooked this move.
Black to play and draw.
Black has a perpetual check.

Now no help would be 32. Qb1 Qc3+ when the best White has is 33. Qc2.  Otherwise the move 33. Kd1 actually loses after 33... Bc4!  threatening 34. ... Qe3! and 35... Bb3+.  White has an interesting response with 34. e5!! where the aforementioned plan fails after 34... Qe3? 35. Qc2 Bb3?? 36. Rc8+ Kd7 37. e6+ winning.  So instead Black would play 34... Qd4+!! 35. Kc1 Qe3+ 36. Kb2 Qxe5+! 37. Kc1 Kc8! and the rook does not have a safe square to move to.  If instead 37. Ka3 Bxd5 and White has the same problem.  If 37. Kc2 Bd3+!  If 35. Ke1? Qe3+ 36. Kd1 Be2+ wins.
Draw by repetition.

Hi everyone!

I did promise you a return to another mating attack, but before I could annotate that one, this game finished on me.  I was facing Class A opposition in this game.  In this MT I drew my game with Rex with the black pieces and here is the return leg with me with the white pieces. The endgame became a same colour bishop ending and evolved into a K&P ending.  I feel this is also worthy of endgame study.  Did Henry come out trumps or did he end up in the Zugzwang?  To find out you must read on or you can read the GA analysis provided. http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=27042198&rnd=0.4446714573088253

I've tried the Old Stenitz (3...d6) as a regular opponent plays it with some success. But I always seem to get a poor game from it, so I stick to a mainline.
Again, I've come untsuck with the Open Defence (5...Nxe4) though an opponent who played it against me won comfortably. Maybe I just don't have the right temperament?!
Time to drive away the Bishop.
And add support to my e-pawn and release my light-squared Bishop.
Preparing to hit the centre.
All very mainline so far.
White has to decide whether to use a tempo to prevent the 9...Bg4 pin, and here he does.

Since I can't pin the Knight I go for the long diagonal. Fischer, incidentally, considered this move too passive, and a premature commitment for the Bishop, with 9...Na5 10.Bc2 c5 being more usual. But I don't like putting my Knight on a5 and driving the Bishop to where it wants to go anyway. And where else is my light-squared Bishop going to go? Tsk, what does Bobby know?

My Knight remains stubbornly on c3, so the Bishop goes to c2 anyway. He could have gone for the centre right away with 10.d4, when I may well have had to play 10...Na5 to get my c-pawn challenging the centre.

Since White hasn't played 10.d4 and 10...Na5 is rather pointless now I decide to retreat the Knight to enable my c-pawn to advance. It's headed for d7, where it can support my pawn, when it gets to c5, and also defend my e-pawn.
I have rather a cramped position. Some typically Lopez shufflin follows...
With a pawn on c3 the Knight has to go via d2 and f1 to get to a decent position, blocking the dark-squared Bishop in the process.
I feel I must challenge the centre, the pricve being that backward d-pawn.

I'm not sure this is White's best plan; it blocks my light-squared Bishop (Bobby was right after all) but doesn't make it easy for White's own light-squared Bishop to get into play, since the centre is rather blocked.
Getting myself a nice pawn chain and (I thought) a nice post for my Knight.
White carries on with the laborious Lopez set-up.
I take up my post. For some reason I didn't think White would try to drive it away with b4.
Indeed, he gets his Knight over to the K-side ready to take part in an attack.
Yes, Bobby was right; I should have left the Bishop here until I had a better square for it. But returning to base now allows White to create a problem for me.
I shy away from opening the c-file and return the Knight. I have wasted far too many moves, but fortunately that White pawn on e4 is rather cramping White's game.
I'm not sure where this is headed; I'm probably okay with giving up my rather useless Bishop (the one on e7 not the equally useless one on f8) - maybe this is the start of an attack on weak d-pawn?

If White doesn't take the Bishop (and the Knight would have made 5 moves to take a piece that's moved once if he does) I intend to get the Bishop back to base on f1. It's very defensive play, but I have been trounced in the Lopez with K-side attacks.
Looking rather dangerous now, and releasing the diagonal for the Queen.
At least g7 is defended.

White switches sides and is tying me in all sorts of knots. I really don't want to allow the light-squared Bishop in by capturing on a4, but my b-pawn is rather hanging since my Rook on a8 is undefended. There's only one thing for it....
First drive away the Knight; I don't want to be fighting on both sides. At this, and other times, I was wary of a piece sacrfice by taking this advanced h-pawn. But I don't think it works here...
The Knight retreats
And my Bishop goes back to its other useless square.
White tries another route.
Allowing the Knight on d7 to go to f6. And revealing a threat to White's own over-eager Knight.
I have, I think, a solid defence!
Time for more position juggling; I want to get my Bishop into the game, which means moving my Queen so my Q-Rook is defended. But I really don't fancy White's Bishop going to b6, if that's his idea.
So I stay on the same diagonal.
Another try, this time allowing the Queen to join an attack
I can't see any other option to get my Bishop into play (I should have listened to Bobby)
Looking to remove on defender, I guess.
Finally. Back where it started for the second time. As is my other Bishop! But that one is at least serving a useful purpose in case of that piece sacrifice on h6.
Now White has only one Knight defending to think about.
I've had it with this Bishop - it's been useless from the start. Time fo it to go.
I wondered whether, as ugly as it would have looked, recapturing with the pawn would have given White better chances?
Offering an exchange, since my Queen is proving as useless as my Bishop was.
White declines, though with the two Bishops he might have done better exchanging?
I want to get my Bishop onto g5 if I can; White's attack is starting to look threatening.
Since the Bishop is no longer protecting g7 the awful threat of 31.Bxh6 looms.
I defend and drive away the Queen.
And return to f6 after the threat has gone. I wondered if White would repeat moves here; I'd have probably been happy with a draw at this point; I've had little of the game.
Instead, and maybe due to frustration, he launches a pawn advance. I'm really not so sure about this?
Continuing to control g5.
Preparing to advance the f-pawn too, I thought.
Time to exchange Bishops; it has nowhere to go, though whether exchanging was best for White I am not sure; had I exchanged it would have rather opened the game up for him.
I'd overlooked that this could be played even with my Bishop on g5. I don't have much choice.
Now that d-pawn is looking vulnerable, and White has the file half-open to attack f7.
Threatening a winning fork on h3 and attacking the e-pawn.
Now I start to build up pieces against White's e-pawn, and suddenly it's that pawn that looks vulnerable.
The Knight is driven back though. But it can re-route to f6.

At the time I thought this an error, even the game's turning point; I expected 39.e5, forcing (?) 39...dxe5 and leaving White with a passed pawn. But after 40.Rxe5 Rxe5 41.Qxe5 Qxg4+ is surely compensation? Anyway, the Q-side is closed and my Rook can move from a8. But first...
That pawn is going no further; hard to see how this Rook can be easily dislodged?
White wants to attack the f-pawn, but this just removes a defender of his own pawn.
And I can block the attack on the f-pawn and build up again on the e-pawn. The game is building up to crisis point.
With the Rook here White can defend on e1 with the other Rook.
Except now 42.Re1 doesn't work because of 42...Nxd5 when the e-pawn is pinned.
Seems White is giving up his pawn for an attack of his own.
A Knight loose in your defence when the Queen and both Rooks are about can be lethal if you're not careful.
I imagine White is as happy to get rid of this Bishop as I was to get rid of mine.
Now the Queen joins in and it looks like a heavy attack on f7.
I kept looking at Qa7+ but I couldn't see anything to follow up. This seemed the safest option.
Possibly getting ready to advance the g-pawn? At present I can't see how White can win that f-pawn.
I could have done this the move before, but I didn't think of it: 46.Rxf7 Rxf1+ followed by 47...Qxf7 is nice.
I thought about 47...Rc1 but that seemed to take the Rook out of the game.
Instead, I keep the White King penned in. I realise that White can now win his pawn back...
And he does.
But surely loses the game in doing so? (Actually, 48...Qxh4+ would have won the game more quickly; 49.Qg3 Rf1 50.Kxf1 Qxg3)
That pawn on d5 is dead.
I still need to be a little careful of the White King penetrating.
I really can't see how he can stop me now.
He can't stop my pawn, so is hoping for some kind of blunder to let him in...
No reason to worry about his pawns though. And he resigned.

Black brings out more firepower and checks the white king mercilessly.

The black queen puts the white king out of his misery.   It was a short game and a very unusual one.  I was able to beat a player who was rated 150 points higher than me.  It is a proud day.

Hi everyone!

This is the game that I promised to show you which starts off as another Reti Opening.  In the middlegame one player sees the opportunity to attack, firstly by a pawn storm, then sacrificing a piece for two pawns and then a queen joins in the fun, but which queen, is it the black queen or is it Glenda?  To find out you will just have to read on.  Here is the GA analysis. http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=27160383&rnd=0.5152885048607565
5. c4 - over the past few moves I have been establishing a strong pawn centre.  If I had a pawn on f4 this would transpose into the Pirc Defense/Austrian Attack.
7. a3 - discouraging either Bb4 or Nb4.
8. h3 - I now prevent Ng4.
9. Qd2 - should the BK go kingside then I will exchange Fou Lenoir for black's dark square bishop leaving black vulnerable on the black squares and Glenda taking full advantage of this.
10. Bd3 - for now though I continue to develop and watch where black puts his king.
11. b4 - goodness gracious, great wall of pawns!
13. 0-0 - I finally choose the kingside and black chooses the queenside.  Suddenly I unleash a pawn storm.
15. a4 - like this!
16. ..... Qd7 - first blood to Yours Truly.  If the BQ should recapture on d6 then the BQ and the knight on f6 will be caught in a pawn fork.  As a result I go a pawn up and a passer at that!
17. e5 - and I now back it up and put the question to the knight on f6.
20. Rfc1+ - after a knight trade and a pawn trade the c file has been opened.  I seize on this immediately and use my king rook as I feel that the other rook will be needed to rake down the a column.
20. ..... Nc6 - black defends by interposition but now, here comes ........ wait for it .........
21. Bxb5 ...... wait for it .......
22. Qxb5 - NOW!! - that was the bishop sac!  The BK has been denuded of pawn cover and just look at whose come to boogie!  GLENDA!!
22. .... Kb8 - pinbreaker and here comes a deathly quiet move just one square from Glenda - to b6.  Black's light square bishop is now horribly pinned.
24. b5 - attacking the knight.  This knight is doomed because if it moves then Qa7+ is mate due to the fact that the c file will be open to my rook on c1.
24. ....Rc8 - stops the mate but black will now lose heavy material.
28. Rc1 - the BQ is pinned and lost.

29. ..... Bxc6 - trying to get as much material back for his queen as possible.  However, after gatecrashing black's party and doing a lot of boogie boogie in black's position, Glenda is feeling HOT, HOT, HOT!

30. Qc7 MATE!! - Yup, the BK now feels the deadly white heat of Glenda and is given The Kiss of Death (this is what this type of support mate is sometimes known as). This is Glenda's dream role, to be delivering checkmate at close range (I can think of nothing more empowering than that) and not defending pawns, vital though that role is, and getting bogged down by passivitis into the bargain.  Sadly, Glenda will never now be able to do that to Freddy the Master Mater (Easy 19) as he has now quit gameknot to pursue a walking career.  Still, there are lots of other big fish in Gameknot's sea that Glenda may prevail against and I must hold on to that belief as I continue my career of being Club Founder of Walking the Walk and Learning to Run.  In every game, no matter how passive I may get, I will always be on the lookout for ways to go for the jugular and nail my opponent's king.  Kind regards - Joanne

Here is another knight endgame and this is going to be quite a marathon.  70 moves are to be played in this one.  Here is the gameknot analysis -enjoy!  http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=26564274&fb=1&rnd=0.24557254462093247
2. Bc4 - in response to a double king pawn opening we have the Bishop's Opening.
4. .... Nf6 - both players bring out their pieces quickly.

8. ..... a6 - uh oh!  Better create a bolt hole for Fou Lenoir!
10. ..... Be6 - clearing the decks and preparing a bishop trade.
14. Qc2 - hmm - white declines a queen trade.  I smell a possible threat of Qxh7#  way way down the line.  I now play the prophylactic h6 to prevent a knight from landing on g5.

16. ..... Ng6 - that pin on the f2 pawn could be useful for a possible kingside mating attack from yours truly.  Maybe I could provoke a few weaknesses in white's castled position and that h3 pawn could suddenly become vulnerable if I can put my knight on f4 like I did in the Chorba game two annotations ago.  That game ended with Chorba copping Old Matey.
18. .... Nf4 - nacht.
20. ...Qg6 - yup, just like the Chorba game only it is Glenda on g6 and not a rook.
21.  .... Bxe3 - threatening mate on g2.
23. Qf2 - the WQ defends.
24. .... Qh7 Glenda manoeuvres herself into a defensive position but not for long!
28. .... Ng7 - start of a regrouping.
31. ..... h5 - threatening to open up the WK by playing g4.
33. ...... Qxe4 - Glenda comes out of hiding and turns white's e4 pawn into dust.  She also defends the pawn on g4.
37. Kxg2 - a queen trade but the plethora of exchanges are not over yet.  Notice that the mating attack has forced white to debunk 2 pawns.
41. Kg7 - we are now in a N v B endgame with me 2 pawns up but with still some work to do.
44. .... b6 - trying to trap the white bishop but alas it does not succeed.
47. .... Kg6 - it looks as though I am going nowhere but with a 2 pawn advantage I am loathe to hit the offer draw button.  I will be patient and wait for white to make an error.
50. Be1 - I expected Bd8 leading to a queenside pawn trade.
52. .... f4 - I am prepared to give back one of my pawns to try and get white into a lost K&P ending.
53. ..... Kf5 - white chooses to keep the pieces on.  Henry now gives my passed pawn on f5 some support.

56. .... Bxc7 - now the c pawns are traded off.  Henry is also eyeing up a white p(r)awn on d5.  I must remind you that prawns are Henry's special dish no matter on what platter and how they are served up.

59. ..... Nxd5+ - the white bishop is sacrificed to try and prevent my pawns reaching Glendadom.  However, there are still two black pawns on the board and only one white one.  I also have an extra piece.
60. ..... Nc3 - this knight will cut off the WK from approaching b1.
63. ..... Kxa5 - yum yum!
65. .... Kb3 - now Henry cuts off the WK from c2.  My a pawn is now has a clear run to Glendadom.
68. Kc1 - it must be beginning to dawn on white that he cannot cut off my a pawn.
70....... a1/Q - However, with this move the mere sight of Glenda induces white to wave the white flag. I will have another endgame for you to peruse shortly.  Kind regards - Joanne
My season has been pretty bad so far - 5 draws and 1 loss in the 4NCL. At last I get to win a game!
I play my trusted Sicilian.
He plays the main line.
I sometimes also play 2.....Nc6
Aiming for d2-d4.
Attacking e4.
Defending e4, although there is no danger as 4.....Nxe4 is met with 5. Qa4+ winning the knight on e4. My opponent said afterwards that he should have played 4. h3
Played, before he can get h3 in....
He attacked my bishop.
I retreated. Probably exchanging on f3 is better. Now I get into an uncomfortable position.
He advances.
I take.
He throws in a check, so that he can recapture the pawn on e5.
In the two games in the Gameknot World Database with this position, black played Nb-d7 and won both games, but I didn't like the look of the position after 8. Nxe5
He takes the pawn.
Defending and attacking.
He takes.
Of course, if I take with the queen, I lose to 10. Bb5
I can't take his bishop on d3 as my c6 pawn goes with check, followed by the Ra8.
So I quietly develop.
Threat 12. Bb7
Easily met.
So he develops.
So do I.
His rook comes to a more active square.
And I castle at last.
His knight reaches a fine blocking square. There is the threat of 15. Ne5 and if 15.....Rb6 16. Bc4 and my a7 pawn goes.
So I stop that.
Strange move by the knight. It was already placed on its best square on c4.
Queen drops back. I was half expecting 16. Nc4 with a repetition and an early draw.
He develops.
So do I.
With a threat of 18. Bf4
I stop that, but it is a bit weakening. I think now 17....Bf6 was better.
Attack!
Defend!
Attack on Bh5
I drop back.
I didn't mind this at first, as I thought he had taken the pressure off my e pawn, but I soon find he has the wonderful e4 square for his knight.
I hit his queen.
Queen switches to the king-side.
Bishop drops back.
Knight takes up a commanding position.
My queen drops back. 23. Bh6 looks strong now, but I can defend with g7-g6 (but not Bf8?? 24. Nxf6! winning).
So he attacks c5 instead.
I open an attack on b2.
So he prevents that.
The only way to stop going a pawn down.
He takes back.
I threaten Qxf5
He protects, also threatening f5xg6 and a second attack on f6 with his rook.
So protect f6 again.
Another attack on g6.
So I try to block off the king-side.
He exchanges off my good bishop.
So off it goes.
He takes back.

and my queen prepares to protect the light squares round my king. He probably has a slight edge here, good knight on e4 v my bad bishop, but I think black should be able to defend. However he now thinks he has a good sacrifice.
He takes.
I take back.
He advances.
I take.
He takes back.
I take.
He takes.
My king runs.
Checks again.
I run again.
Check again.
My king runs again. Now this position is lost for black, just one pawn for a rook. I think the best way to fight on is to take the second pawn and hope for the best. Instead he plays a little trap.
What would you play here for black dear reader?
Did you find it? Of course, if I take the rook immediately, 37. Qxc6 is mate.
King moves.
I take.
He takes.

and, two rooks down, white resigns. Thank you for reading. Please leave a comment or two, and rate it on the star system to let me know how I am doing with my annotations. Until next time dear reader!

I offered a draw and white accepted my offer. I am black
First move that deviated from the usual lines. It's interesting, I can use the pin on Nf3 and press on f2. But I was playing with fear, so I take the tempo to cover my Be6.

In this opening, Ng5 threats NxBe6, leaving me with a very weak, isolated pawn, and I have to prevent it. This means to castle (queenside, of course, since I plan a pawn attack on the Kside), and very quickly, so to be able to play Bf5 in case of Ng4. All that, taking care of Nxf7.
If Re1, o-o-o, it is still possible for white to sac the exchange (RxBe6), and go on with a nice game.
More accurate can be Qa5, then g5, and then Bd6, taking control of the diagonal.
The bad side of this exchange is that now I don't have anymore the Nc5 thrust, taking advantage of the pinned d pawn. Too bad.
Going after my castled K.
More accurate is g5, going for my own pawn storm.
The known sac of a piece for two pawns was tempting me, but hey, against a 1800... I had to play with care! If he allows it, he must be sure it isn't sound.
Well... it doesn't sound like a 1800 move, isn't it? Still, I am wondering why he doesn't play d5 at once, which is the move I have to fear.
Now I have to figure out how to play h5 without losing g5.
...but again, I was playing with fear, so I preferred to offer a R's exchange and see what happens.
What I am not seeing?
My Q blocks his planned b4. Now he should play d5,

Ok, he plans Ra4, and I have to be careful about where to put my Q. I thought that "of course" Qxb2 was bad, just opening columns for him to attack my castled K. As I said, "playing with fear", but it was sound.
If Ra4, NxN. If he doesn't go for the exchange, Ne2+ and I'll win the R.
If Qc4, Nd2 and I lose my beloved lsb. Fear pays.
Alea iacta est: counterattacking.
? I expected some pawn advance on the Qside.
...can't be so easy. What am I missing?
If Qxh6, Qb2.
My K controls the f column, unles...
I am glad with a draw (again a 1800).
It seems a bad choice, and it is: Now, Rf2+, Rd7, RxR, KxR, axb6 and I am lost. My K doesn't have time to take on b6 before it is defended by the c pawn.
? Even if my pawns get splitted, this gives life to my K as an active piece.
Draw is assured. If Rf5+, Ka4 and I'll threaten his pawns from the back. He has to exchange R in order to take my h pawn, and this will give me time to grab his pawns.
Now I am even winning!
He resigned here. 1800? No. It was his first game, his rating was only temporary. But playing "as he was a 1800" paid, even with my usual blunders. Thanks for reading and commenting!

El ajedrez se trata de crear figuras geométricas con los elementos que nos dan. El ajedrecista es como un albañil que tiene que construir puntos fuertes dentro de la estructura del adversario desde donde amenace el adversario. Entonces que elementos de construcción tenemos. Diagonales, que la hacen los alfiles, Columnas, que las hacen las torres, Vigas o filas, que las hacen las torres. Remaches, que los hacen los caballos y los peones. La dama tiene varias propiedades y el rey todas las debilidades. Una diagonal de peones fortalece la diagonal que ocupa y deja debilitada la diagonal que no ocupa. Dos peones en el centro fortalecen las cuatro casillas sobre las que influencian y debilitan las dos casillas de los costados. Dejamos un punto debil cuando hay un peon atrasado y uno adelantado. El punto debil esta en el costado del peon adelantado y el frente del peon atrasado. Entonces desde ese punto domina la situacion la pieza que pongamos. Es un lugar para ocupar, donde no puede ser desalojada la pieza. Pero eso solo no hace ganar la partida. hay que ver el concepto y el modo de usarlo. las diagonales o columnas o filas que dominan las otras piezas se pueden obstruir con una pieza nuestra que este defendida. También se puede desviar las piezas contrarias.
Con la apertura del blanco le dimos lugar a las diagonales del alfil y la dama, lo mismo hizo el negro.
el blanco amenazo el punto en e5 y el negro lo defendio con su peon.
Con este avance del peon el negro debilita dramaticamente la diagonal que va de h5 a e8. Debe haber una compensación a esta debilidad que da mas ventaja que esta terrible desventaja
El blanco amenaza comer la dama negra , pero previamente el negro habia amenazado la casilla f2 con su alfil y de ese modo puede sacar su dama hacia un lugar donde amenace la casilla f2 .

La dama puede ocupar esa columna y construir una estructura donde la diagonal del alfil negro de casillas negras refuerza el punto f2 porque previamente cambio su peon que obstruia esta construccion . esta debe ser la compensación a la terrible debilidad que comente previamente
este avance de peon libera la fila 2 para que la domine totalmente la dama negra.

el negro aprovecha la ventaja de la liberación de la fila para el dominio de la dama negra amenazando con su caballo la casilla c2 . El blanco antes de avanzar el peon debería haber jugado su peon de a2 a a3.

aca cuando el negro toma con el rey, no puede el blanco tomar con el peon, porque debilita su diagonal de e1 a a5. Entonces el blanco se ve obligado a tomar con la dama . La fortaleza del negro esta en ocupar con su dama la fila segunda y en la amenaza de ocupar la diagonal con el alfil negro. Las dos solas , la fila y la diagonal no sirven . Lo que sirve es la combinacion del dominio de la fila y el dominio de la diagonal.
